{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bd59e751-20da-49d7-8836-fb13276c6478","content":"## What happened\n\n.NET 11 removed the built-in DSA implementation on macOS. Apple's native crypto framework (`Security.framework`) has **never** supported DSA, and .NET previously shipped a managed/OpenSSL-backed shim. With .NET 11, that shim was dropped, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nThis doesn't affect Windows (CNG supports DSA) or Linux (OpenSSL supports DSA).\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures, use **BouncyCastle**, which provides a fully managed DSA implementation that runs everywhere:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the built-in DSA calls with BouncyCastle's:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(\n    byte[] publicKeyDer, byte[] message, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var publicKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)\n        PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);\n\n    var signer = new DsaSigner();\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n\n    // Decode the DER-encoded signature into (r, s)\n    var seq = (Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Sequence)\n        Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Object.FromByteArray(signature);\n    var r = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)seq[0]).Value;\n    var s = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)seq[1]).Value;\n\n    // Hash the message with SHA-1 (typical for legacy DSA)\n    var digest = Org.BouncyCastle.Security.DigestUtilities.CalculateDigest(\"SHA-1\", message);\n\n    return signer.VerifySignature(digest, r, s);\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- BouncyCastle is pure managed C# — no platform dependencies\n- Works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS\n- No need to install OpenSSL on macOS\n- Long-term, plan to migrate away from DSA entirely (it's cryptographically weak by modern standards)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"35dc0ed7-bf15-4c5b-8120-9bf4334b6a49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been a target. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET 7+, there were breaking changes around cryptographic APIs on macOS. Specifically, Apple's Security framework (via CommonCrypto/SecKey) doesn't support DSA, and .NET on macOS relied on OpenSSL for DSA support. \n \nI need to reconsider the timeline here—the user is upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, which would be future versions. Let me think through the .NET release schedule to understand when these versions would be available and what breaking changes might be relevant.\n\nThe core issue seems to be around DSA support on macOS. In .NET 7, there was a significant shift where `DSA.Create()` started throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because .NET moved away from using OpenSSL and switched to Apple's native cryptographic APIs, which don't support DSA. If the user's code worked on .NET 10 but broke on .NET 11, there might be an additional deprecation or removal happening in that version.\n\nThe solution likely involves either migrating away from DSA entirely or finding an alternative approach if they only need to verify existing signatures rather than create new ones. signatures on macOS since Apple's Security framework doesn't support DSA natively. For verifying legacy signatures, BouncyCastle is the most practical solution since it provides a managed DSA implementation that works cross-platform, whereas switching to RSA or ECDSA isn't an option when the signatures are already in DSA format.","outputTokens":1755},"id":"7b28d026-3324-4c7f-be5c-58